Neuroblastoma Cell Line: Differential expression analysis with DESeq2

CCDL 2018

In this notebook, well perform an analysis to identify the genes that are differentially expressed in MYCN amplified vs.nonamplified neuroblastoma cell lines.

These RNA-seq data are from Harenza, et al. Scientific Data. 2017..

More information about DESeq2 can be found in the excellent vignette from Love, Anders, and Huber from which this is adapted (see also: Love, Anders, and Huber. Genome Biology. 2014.)

DESeq2 takes unnormalized counts or estimated counts does the following:

  • Estimates size factors
  • Estimates dispersion
  • Negative binomial generalized linear model fitting and Wald statistics

DESeq2

Creating a DESeq2 dataset from tximport object

First, lets read in the data we processed with tximport.

txi <- readr::read_rds(txi_file)

Now, the sample metadata.

sample_meta_df <- readr::read_tsv(meta_file)
Parsed with column specification:
cols(
  Sample_SRR_accession = col_character(),

sample_meta_df

Were most interested in MYCN amplification, which is in the Status column of sample_meta_df

head(sample_meta_df$Status)
[1] "Amplified" "Amplified" "Amplified" "Amplified" "Amplified" "Amplified"

Lets check that the ordering of samples is the same.

all.equal(colnames(txi$counts), sample_meta_df$Sample_SRR_accession)
[1] "23 string mismatches"

Lets reorder by Sample_SRR_accession and see if that remedies the ordering.

sample_meta_df <- sample_meta_df %>%
  dplyr::arrange(Sample_SRR_accession)
all.equal(colnames(txi$counts), sample_meta_df$Sample_SRR_accession)
[1] TRUE

It worked!

Dataset creation

ddset <- DESeqDataSetFromTximport(txi = txi,
                                  colData = sample_meta_df,
                                  design = ~ Status)
some variables in design formula are characters, converting to factorsusing counts and average transcript lengths from tximport

Differential expression

Preparation

Lets do some pre-filtering to keep rows with 10 or more reads total.

genes_to_keep <- rowSums(counts(ddset)) >= 10
ddset <- ddset[genes_to_keep, ]

Well want to use the Nonamplified samples as our reference. Lets look at the levels of Status.

levels(ddset$Status)
[1] "Amplified"    "Nonamplified"

We can see that these are in alphabetical order, so Amplified samples would be the reference. We can use the relevel function to remedy this.

ddset$Status <- relevel(ddset$Status, ref = "Nonamplified")
levels(ddset$Status)
[1] "Nonamplified" "Amplified"

Visualize differentially expressed genes with a heatmap

Lets get an overall picture of our results using a heatmap. Before we can do this, we will need to transform our data so that when we make the heatmap the genes are on a more similar scale and the heatmap is interpretable. We will use variance stablizing transformation (VST) from DESeq2 to do this. Refer to the help page or the DESeq2 docs for more information.

vst_data <- vst(ddset)
using 'avgTxLength' from assays(dds), correcting for library size

We need to extract the normalized gene matrix from the vst_data object.

vst_data <- assay(vst_data)

We will make a heatmap of only the significant genes, so lets obtain the gene IDs that have an adjusted p-value less than 0.05.

signif_genes <- deseq_df %>%
  dplyr::filter(padj < 0.05) %>%
  dplyr::pull(Gene)

Now we will use signif_genes to filter vst_data to only have significant genes data.

signif_vst_data <- vst_data %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  dplyr::filter(rownames(vst_data) %in% signif_genes)

Lets make the results into a heatmap using the pheatmap package. We will use the scale = "row" argument so that the data is standardized by gene (i.e will be made into z-scores). Standardizing the data by gene makes it so our heatmap is more easily interpretable despite how different genes distributions may be.

pheatmap::pheatmap(signif_vst_data, 
                   show_rownames = FALSE,
                   scale = "row",
                   colorRampPalette(c("deepskyblue",
                                      "black",
                                      "yellow"))(25))

We go over heatmaps in greater depth in the machine learning module.
